{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":229710,"duration_api_ms":229531,"num_turns":4,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"7928baa9-593f-45d3-a51b-ed700be0cac9","total_cost_usd":0.6134567500000001,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":27119,"cache_read_input_tokens":111981,"output_tokens":3267,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":27119,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":5,"outputTokens":3267,"cacheReadInputTokens":111981,"cacheCreationInputTokens":27119,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.30718425000000005,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":185,"outputTokens":12211,"cacheReadInputTokens":1464125,"cacheCreationInputTokens":78896,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.30627250000000006,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All three amendments identify genuine issues. Amendment fr-18-e23d3048 is the most critical — it identifies a real bug where snapshot write failure in the retry-backoff path leaves run.json in an inconsistent state. Amendment fr-18-86b3413e correctly calls for test coverage of the new mandatory error propagation. Amendment fr-18-4d7180f4 correctly identifies that the jitter implementation's comments overstate what the hash-mixing actually achieves for same-tick calls.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-18-86b3413e","decision":"accept","rationale":"The behavioral change from best-effort (log+swallow) to mandatory (`?` propagation) at engine.rs:4649 is significant and deserves explicit test coverage. The FailingSnapshotWrite fixture already exists in conformance_spec/scenarios.rs, making this straightforward to implement. The two-part verification — (a) engine returns error on snapshot write failure, and (b) derive_resume_state reconstructs correctly from journal alone — directly validates the invariant the code change depends on: that the journal is the authoritative source of truth. This test also serves as a regression guard for the bug identified in amendment fr-18-e23d3048."},{"amendment_id":"fr-18-e23d3048","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a genuine bug. The code path is: (1) stage_failed journal event is durably appended, (2) snapshot is mutated to Failed status, (3) write_run_snapshot(...) is called with `?`. If step 3 fails (disk full, permissions), the `?` propagates the error directly out of execute_stage_with_retry. The caller at line 3307 also uses `.await?`, so the error continues up. Critically, this error bypasses fail_run_result — the function that would normally write RunStatus::Failed to run.json and append a run_failed journal event. The result: run.json remains in its prior Running state while the journal contains a stage_failed event, creating exactly the journal/snapshot divergence the comments at lines 4643-4648 warn about. The daemon loop's mark_failed only updates the daemon task record, not run.json. The fix should catch the snapshot write error and route it through fail_run_result, or at minimum log-and-continue (the previous behavior) since the journal is authoritative and the snapshot will be stale but not contradictory."},{"amendment_id":"fr-18-4d7180f4","decision":"accept","rationale":"The technical analysis is correct. The apply_jitter function derives its entire random input from SystemTime::now().subsec_nanos(). The Murmur-style hash mixing is a deterministic function — it improves the distribution of different nanos values across the output range, but two calls with identical nanos input produce identical output. On platforms with 1ms or 10ms clock resolution, calls within the same tick will compute the same jitter factor. The code comments at lines 139-142 claim the mixing step prevents 'identical jitter for closely-spaced calls', which is inaccurate — it only prevents linearly correlated outputs for different-tick calls. While the practical impact is reduced because sequential retries within a single run are unlikely to collide, the code's claims don't match its behavior. A thread-local RNG (even a simple xorshift seeded once from system time + thread ID) or mixing in a monotonic counter would genuinely solve the problem the comments describe."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"1e317147-db30-4218-9827-f00718f370e2"}
